1
00:00:00,655 --> 00:00:27,085
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhudassam

2
00:00:27,469 --> 00:00:53,207
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One So the word is Khanda So we'll do the Khanda which is the Buddha's way of understanding the psychosomatic, psychophysical organism Khanda, K-H-A-N-D-H-A

3
00:00:53,186 --> 00:00:57,316
And it's translated as aggregate or heat.

4
00:00:58,518 --> 00:01:01,003
So it's like concrete for instance.

5
00:01:01,064 --> 00:01:08,260
A bit of cement, a bit of sand, a bit of stone, a bit of water and it creates something solid.

6
00:01:08,813 --> 00:01:10,835
That's the point, you see.

7
00:01:10,855 --> 00:01:17,444
We experience ourselves as solid entities, human beings.

8
00:01:19,025 --> 00:01:24,072
And what the Buddha was always doing is deconstructing our experience.

9
00:01:24,093 --> 00:01:32,765
So in dependent origination, he deconstructs it in a timeline as to how we create the world one moment after another.

10
00:01:33,525 --> 00:01:36,930
But in the aggregates, it's more like a slice, a slice of life.

11
00:01:37,450 --> 00:01:45,664
And if you look at the human being as a psychophysical organism, he divides it into these five parts.

12
00:01:46,426 --> 00:01:53,518
And over the next few weeks I'll go into the five parts in more detail.

13
00:01:55,405 --> 00:01:59,290
So we do that with everything in the world.

14
00:01:59,712 --> 00:02:06,882
We create a concept, we have a designation, and we concretize things into things.

15
00:02:07,343 --> 00:02:09,086
So very simply, a tree.

16
00:02:09,627 --> 00:02:11,349
When you look at a tree, you see a tree.

17
00:02:11,811 --> 00:02:17,218
You call it a tree and you see it as a whole, as an entity, you might say.

18
00:02:17,780 --> 00:02:21,665
But we're well aware that the tree is made up of leaves, branches, and so on.

19
00:02:22,372 --> 00:02:45,830
and when you go into the leaves and branches and so on you get molecules and molecules you get subatomic particles you just get energy so it's that way of deconstructing things but all that still remains is a concept I mean science tells us that everything is just pure energy but we don't experience it like that we experience things as things quite solid

20
00:02:47,818 --> 00:02:57,046
When you fall over and bang your head on a rock like I did, you don't think this is subatomic particles meeting subatomic particles.

21
00:02:57,729 --> 00:02:59,634
It's doing that.

22
00:03:00,997 --> 00:03:07,526
And the image that the Buddha uses as a way of, you know, he's always using metaphors, is a cart.

23
00:03:08,026 --> 00:03:14,314
So in his day, a cart, it looks like a cart, but of course it's made up of a wheel, axles, the main body of it, and so on.

24
00:03:15,417 --> 00:03:23,326
And it's the same with things that we own, like a car or a television, see, it has a

25
00:03:23,475 --> 00:03:43,407
the mind is able to create solidity, substance, that's the point and of course this comes very close to us when it comes to our own bodies so this designation that we give to ourselves, this concept

26
00:03:43,556 --> 00:04:06,830
where we draw all our experience together as it were and create me, a me, the solider that's what he is trying to deconstruct, the self, a person and he does it in five modes, so the part of it is corporeality, the body

27
00:04:07,300 --> 00:04:34,944
then there's all the business of perceptions which go really from just the original percepts that come into the senses to conceptual thinking it's that whole business of how the mind creates how the mental part of our experience is created then there's all the feelings which are both physical feelings coming from the body but also feelings coming from the mind

28
00:04:35,413 --> 00:04:40,663
that we normally call emotions or moods, but they're actual feelings in the body.

29
00:04:41,846 --> 00:04:45,894
Then there's this whole business of, translated as volitional conditioning.

30
00:04:46,233 --> 00:04:49,680
So that, you might say, is our thought in the emotional life.

31
00:04:50,862 --> 00:04:53,928
But it's where the will comes in, it's where we create things.

32
00:04:54,382 --> 00:05:05,721
Our conditionings which we then split into those things where we feel unhappy and those things where we feel happy.

33
00:05:06,262 --> 00:05:08,307
That's basically how we experience life.

34
00:05:10,632 --> 00:05:13,598
And finally there's the act of cognition.

35
00:05:17,887 --> 00:05:19,430
I'll go into it in a bit more detail.

36
00:05:20,310 --> 00:05:24,579
It's the point where all this information is gathered on a screen.

37
00:05:25,021 --> 00:05:27,105
It's a primary knowing.

38
00:05:27,220 --> 00:05:47,017
if you think of a television and all the things that actually move within the television coming from outside all the radio waves, television waves and all that and it's all hitting the TV and inside the TV there's all this mentation going on

39
00:05:47,925 --> 00:06:14,540
and what you've got is a screen in front which collects it all into an image that you then know so it's the same with the mind there's something that gathers it all together and presents it as an image as an act of cognition and all this of course you can actually experience I mean it's not as though these things are in themselves some sort of

40
00:06:14,740 --> 00:06:35,127
idealism or something but let me just quote from the scriptures where he points something out to us there insubstantiality he says suppose that a man who's not blind were to behold the many bubbles in the Ganges as they are driving along and he should watch them and carefully examine them

41
00:06:35,463 --> 00:06:43,071
After carefully examining them, however, they will appear to him empty, unreal and insubstantial.

42
00:06:43,850 --> 00:07:02,230
In exactly the same way does the meditator behold all the corporeal phenomena, feelings, perceptions, mental formations and states of consciousness, whether they be of the past, present or future, far or near, and he watches them and examines them carefully.

43
00:07:02,209 --> 00:07:12,742
and after carefully examining them, they appear to him empty, unreal, and unsubstantial, or insubstantial.

44
00:07:14,461 --> 00:07:24,274
You can do an exercise where you can make at least some of these different candas clear to yourself.

45
00:07:24,293 --> 00:07:25,536
So now it's spring, you see.

46
00:07:25,615 --> 00:07:27,317
There's the daffodils out.

47
00:07:27,338 --> 00:07:37,552
So when you see a daffodil, you see, it's immediately put into the context of all the daffodils and all the flowers you've experienced.

48
00:07:37,572 --> 00:07:39,233
So you don't actually see that daffodil.

49
00:07:39,613 --> 00:07:43,860
It's always that daffodil in comparison with all of the daffodils.

50
00:07:43,839 --> 00:07:46,560
So I actually see that daffodil

51
00:07:46,641 --> 00:08:14,639
you have to put your attention right on it now as you put your attention right on it to as it were close down the mentation around it and all the comparisons and all that past experience you can repeat the simple word like looking not daffodil because that brings all the other stuff in but the action of looking so just by saying looking, looking it as it were collapses the thinking mind

52
00:08:15,024 --> 00:08:18,574
So the thinking mind can only think in words, remember, words and images.

53
00:08:18,935 --> 00:08:30,148
So as you say looking, looking, you see, and that begins to close down, your attention just goes on to the flower itself, on to the actual what it is you're actually perceiving.

54
00:08:30,769 --> 00:08:43,582
And the more and more you do that, you'll see that, you may experience, hopefully, that the door of perception is being cleansed and the yellowness of the flower begins to appear more yellow.

55
00:08:44,183 --> 00:08:55,274
The shape of the flower, the little filigrees and all the little shapes that go into the flower become more obvious as you begin to just focus in, just on the flower as flower.

56
00:08:55,254 --> 00:09:19,407
now as you do that and you become aware just of its yellowness or of its shape that's you're experiencing perception that's the perceiving mind and then as it were you've come from that and you stay perceiving you may also feel that with the perception a feeling arises

57
00:09:19,657 --> 00:09:22,621
In other words, your relationship to that flower.

58
00:09:22,942 --> 00:09:25,687
So there may, hopefully, there'll be a sense of joy, right?

59
00:09:25,706 --> 00:09:27,269
A sense of feeling towards it.

60
00:09:27,951 --> 00:09:31,556
So there's that, and even colors have a feeling, don't they?

61
00:09:32,037 --> 00:09:32,278
You know?

62
00:09:33,318 --> 00:09:37,446
Often I, maybe it's a regression, but often I find...

63
00:09:37,426 --> 00:09:47,559
If I see a real beautiful green or a blue, somehow it takes me back to being around about three, four or five when you play with these blocks that are blue and green.

64
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:49,482
It's a funny sort of thing.

65
00:09:50,082 --> 00:09:53,768
And people get that with music as well, don't they?

66
00:09:53,849 --> 00:09:54,448
Sounds.

67
00:09:55,129 --> 00:10:03,601
So you may actually feel a feeling come up as you experience just the perception of yellowness, right?

68
00:10:05,606 --> 00:10:22,941
then as it were as you come out of that mode of just pure perception and you come away from it and you stop saying knowing then suddenly you get that sort of different level of perception where memory

69
00:10:22,921 --> 00:10:49,991
comes in in a sense of it's comparison with all the other daffodils and flowers you've seen and then you see the judging coming in that it's not such a good daffodil it's a bit corrupt or the yellow or you prefer this yellow to that yellow now presumed on all that process is the act of cognition the act of just that primary knowing

70
00:10:51,692 --> 00:11:20,147
so these are little exercises where you can actually see how the mind is building up the world and in your meditation you may even perceive that in terms of a pain you see so while you're sitting you get pain in the knee so that's your conceptual idea pain in the knee as you go into the pain and really experience the pain as pain not just pain in the knee knee is a concept

71
00:11:20,919 --> 00:11:43,130
as you go into it you might just experience tightness, heat little stabby pains and whatnot and at that point you lose the perception of pain it's just pure feeling and as you back off that suddenly you get the concept come in pain and with pain you get the reaction

72
00:11:44,831 --> 00:11:56,346
So, these things, these little exercises and the process of Vipassana are just ways of breaking down the solidity of how we experience ourselves.

73
00:11:59,510 --> 00:12:10,203
And remember that whenever we're doing that, something is, as it were, emerging out of it, is the point.

74
00:12:10,224 --> 00:12:14,669
The whole point of breaking down the idea of the self is to discover who we really are.

75
00:12:14,903 --> 00:12:25,240
And that which is emerging out of it and getting to know all this as objects and getting to know it as process, you see, that's this satipaṋña.

76
00:12:25,259 --> 00:12:40,725
And it's beginning to recognize what this satipaṋña is as opposed to all the mentation that we experience, which is the process of liberation, detachment.

77
00:12:45,784 --> 00:13:14,897
So that's the khandha, the five khandha, you see the body, corporeality, I'll go into that in more detail next week all our perceptions, memory included in that, you see all our feeling, the feeling base of our experience which is both mental and physical coming from the body, coming from the mind all the things that we create through an act of will

78
00:13:15,956 --> 00:13:42,133
and those are our emotional thought life and then finally this the act of cognition the sort of primary knowing of things I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you be liberated sooner rather than later

79
00:13:44,138 --> 00:13:47,701
God bless you.

